Create a Simple HTML File

1.	Open a text editor and create a new file named index.html.

2.	Add the following HTML content:

3.	<!DOCTYPE html>

4.	<html>

5.	<head>

6.	    <title>Hello, World!</title>

7.	</head>

8.	<body>

9.	    <h1>Hello, World!</h1>

10.	</body>

</html>

11.	Save the file in a new directory (e.g., docker-webpage).

Step 2: Create a Dockerfile

1.	In the same directory, create a file named Dockerfile (without any extension).

2.	Add the following content to the Dockerfile:

3.	# Use an official Nginx image as the base image

4.	FROM nginx:latest

5.	

6.	# Copy the HTML file to the Nginx default directory

7.	COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html

8.	

9.	# Expose port 80

EXPOSE 80

10.	Save the file.

Step 3: Build the Docker Image

1.	Open a terminal or command prompt and navigate to the docker-webpage directory.

2.	Run the following command to build the Docker image:

docker build -t my-html-app .

Step 4: Run the Docker Container

1.	Use the following command to start a container from the built image:

docker run -d -p 8080:80 my-html-app

2.	This maps port 80 of the container to port 8080 of the local machine.

Step 5: View the Webpage

1.	Open a web browser and enter the following URL:

http://localhost:8080

2.	You should see the message "Hello, World!" displayed.

Step 6: Stop and Remove the Container (Optional)

•	To stop the container, run:

•	docker ps   # To find the running container ID

docker stop <container_id>

•	To remove the container, run:

docker rm <container_id>

